</div><div>
<strong>Ministry Leader:</strong> "OK, so you've just learned about these 1=
6 projects for Christmas. When is everything due?"<br><strong>Me:</strong> =
"um, I'm not sure yet. I'll have to work through all these different projec=
ts to get a sense of scope from my team. These projects live across multipl=
e people and the deadlines will be impacted by multiple teams."<br><strong>=
ML:</strong> "Can't you just pick a date and tell them that's when it needs=
 to be done?"<br><strong>Me:</strong> "That's not really how it works"<br><=
strong>ML:</strong> "Well just get it to us ASAP. We have a lot of work to =
do!"<br><br>
</div><div>My initial reaction was to be frustrated at the ministry leader,=
 but they were right. They DID have a lot of work to do. So did my team. Ra=
ther than stewing in the frustration of being put on the spot, I decided to=
 create this tool so I could have an accurate answer every time I was asked=
.<br><br>
</div><div>Each type of project (video, print, etc.) has a different breakd=
own of milestones that were defined by those involved ahead of time. Depend=
ing on the project, you'll want to bring in other teams like Productions, M=
edia, Communications, Worship, etc. to help define the time needed between =
milestones. This allows you to have your timeframes already established and=
 agreed to. Then you just put in the due dates and watch the spreadsheet ca=
lculate your project milestones.<br><br>
</div><div>When your systems are working, your team is healthier!</div></di=
